04649nam a22005535i 9780773588547DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735885477 a10.1515/97807735885472doi  a(DE-B1597)656725  a(OCoLC)844940508  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aMED0390002bisacsh04a613/.043209712231 aGleason, Mona, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSmall Matters :bCanadian Children in Sickness and Health, 1900-1940 /cMona Gleason. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b15 drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Associated Medical Services Studies in the History of Medicine, Health, and Society ;v3900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Intimate Landscape of Health in the History of Children and Childhood -- tDoctored Bodies: Professional Medical Discourse and Children’s Embodied Difference -- tFlorence, Marc, Alice, and Theresa: Healthy Bodies and Domestic Doctoring,1910s to the 1920s -- tShirley, Lily, Jack, and Lina: Healthy Bodies and Domestic Doctoring,1920s to the 1940s -- tLearning the Body: Schools, Curriculum, and Health -- tTreated Bodies: Hospitalization -- tReforming the Body: Doctors, Educators, and Attitudes Towards Disability in Childhood -- tconclusion:Small Matters: Historical Meaning and Children’s Embodiment -- tCauses of Infant Death in Canada, for five-year periods, 1921–50* -- tParticipant Information -- tMy Health Record -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat was it like to be young and sick in the past? Who taught children how to be healthy and what were they expected to learn? In Small Matters, Mona Gleason explores how medical professionals, lay practitioners, and parents understood young patients and how children responded. During the first half of the twentieth century, particularly in the interwar decades, a number of changes took shape within the field of child healthcare - the rise of pediatrics as a medical profession, efforts to ameliorate maternal and infant mortality rates, and the shift of focus from controlling contagious diseases to the prevention of illness. Gleason makes use of oral histories throughout this period of health and welfare reform to shed new light on children's attitudes toward their medical treatment, their largely unexplored experiences of hospitalization and disability, and the importance of teachers and health curriculum to the development of "healthy habits." By focusing on children's medical treatment beyond the doctor's office, and by paying particular attention to the experience of marginalized children, Gleason makes a major contribution to the history of Canadian childhood and healthcare. The first work of its kind, Small Matters explores how children faced death, endured illness, and learned to be healthy in the context of their families and communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild health serviceszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aChildrenxHealth and hygienezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPediatricszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysician and patient. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358854740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588547/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete e